  "planFinal": "1. Define the Scope: Establish the structural hierarchy of the renal system by focusing on macroscopic anatomy (gross morphology, position, and vascular supply) and microscopic anatomy (the nephron structure, including the renal corpuscle and tubular system). Define key functional zones to be investigated, specifically the renal cortex, medulla, pyramids, calyces, and the renal pelvis.\n\n2. Execute Multi-Source Search: Conduct a structured literature search using authoritative medical databases and academic resources. Search for anatomical textbooks (e.g., Gray’s Anatomy), peer-reviewed journals, and verified educational medical portals to gather high-resolution illustrations, diagrams, and descriptive nomenclature regarding renal histology and regional anatomy.\n\n3. Cross-Reference and Analyze: Systematically compare findings across sources to ensure anatomical accuracy. Analyze the spatial relationships between the kidneys and adjacent retroperitoneal structures, and verify the internal architectural details, focusing on the blood filtration path (afferent/efferent arterioles and glomerular filtration barrier) versus the urine collection path.\n\n4. Identify Evidence Gaps: Evaluate the gathered data for potential deficiencies. Look for missing information regarding individual variations, the role of the interstitium, or specific details on neurovascular innervation. If technical depth is insufficient, perform secondary targeted searches focusing on embryological development or clinical correlations that provide context to the anatomical features.\n\n5. Synthesize Findings: Consolidate the verified information into a coherent, structured report. Organize the content from systemic orientation down to cellular-level components, ensuring technical terminology is consistent and accurate. Conclude by summarizing how the structural arrangement directly facilitates the kidney’s physiological function of filtration, reabsorption, and excretion."
